Q: What does the user bring to The Other Side? (Select all that apply)

A: Something they saw — an image, video, article, Something they're in — a personal conflict or situation, Something they believe — an opinion or position, Something they heard — a conversation, a podcast, a speech, They should be able to talk to agent and narrate the situation or just write it up if they prefer or provide weblink  to video, podcast.

Q: What should the agent do first?

A: Jump straight to the other side — no preamble

Q: What's the primary output format?

A: A structured written perspective — factual and grounded



Q: What should the structured output contain? (Select all that apply)

A: Verified facts that challenge the original view, The emotions driving the other side — not just the logic, Where both sides genuinely overlap, What a neutral third party would say, What the other side actually believes and why, the output must be a video, audio and text

Q: How many perspectives should the output show?

A: Depends on the lens the user picks

Q: What tone should the output have?

A: Warm and human — like a trusted friend



Q: When you say video output — what does that look like?

A: A fully generated video with voiceover and scene visuals

Q: For audio — whose voice delivers the other side?

A: A voice that adapts to the emotional tone of the content

Q: After the output is delivered — what happens next?

A: A simple reflection prompt — 'what shifted for you?'



Q: Is this a private tool or a social one — does the user have an identity?

A: Anonymous — no account needed, just use it, 1 and 2

Q: How does this sustain itself?

A: I don't know what's practical, I know users try free stuff and that's easily adapted

Q: Where does someone use The Other Side? (Select all that apply)

A: Chrome Extension — flip anything on any page, Mobile app, Web app, Users must be able to point to the video on the webpage they are on and ask for a different perspective



Q: On privacy — what matters most to you? (Select all that apply)

A: User reflections stay private, never used for training, Input is never stored — processed and discarded, No personal data collected, not even analytics, Transparent about what is and isn't stored, collect data on errors and may be collect user feedback on output. Basically collect non-personal data to continously improve the product.

Q: On toxic content — what should the agent refuse to flip? (Select all that apply)

A: Content targeting a specific real person with harm, Anything that could radicalize or extremise a view further, anything pronographic, child abuse, anything promoting wrong things. Basically a line we want users to use it to see other view, but not misuse to generate wrong ideas and harmful perspectives.

Q: When the agent hits a guardrail — what should it do?

A: Decline silently and explain why it can't proceed



Q: Where should guardrails sit in the pipeline?

A: Both — input scan first, intent check second

Q: What should the decline message sound like — in the voice of the product?

A: Keep it warm — 'This one's outside what I can help with, but here's why'





