Q: These are the gaps I see — which ones matter to you? (Select all that apply)

A: Trust — why should a user believe the facts cited are actually verified, Edge cases — what if the input has no clear 'other side' — e.g. child abuse, genocide, The agent getting it wrong — what if the other side perspective is factually incorrect, Onboarding — how does a first-time user understand what this is in 10 seconds, Misuse at scale — what if someone uses it to generate 1000 fake 'other sides', adjust the screen to different screens and scales and devices perhaps which anyone from grandma to blind to child to adult can use?



Q: On TRUST — how should the agent signal a fact is verified?

A: Both — source link + confidence level

Q: On EDGE CASES — when there's no legitimate other side, what should the agent do?

A: Decline and explain — 'some things don't have another side worth hearing'

Q: On GETTING IT WRONG — how do we handle factual errors?

A: Both — agent flags uncertainty + user can report



Q: ONBOARDING — how does a first-time user get it in 10 seconds?

A: Just throw them in — the experience explains itself

Q: MISUSE AT SCALE — how do we stop bulk fake perspective generation? (Select all that apply)

A: Rate limiting — cap uses per session without an account, Detect patterns — flag repetitive or bulk generation, CAPTCHA or friction for high volume use

Q: ACCESSIBILITY — grandma to blind to child to adult, what's non-negotiable? (Select all that apply)

A: Audio-first mode — full experience without ever reading, High contrast mode available



